    <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to index</a>

    <h1>A Synthetic Approach to Markov Kernels</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Tobias Fritz · 2020 · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1908.07021"><img src="/natural-breadcrumbs/arxiv.webp" alt="arxiv" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/> arXiv:1908.07021</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">No prerequisites. This page and <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/staton-2025/">🍞 Staton 2025</a> are independent entry points.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Stochastic functions form a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category_(mathematics)">🅦 category</a> with copy and discard. Whether a function is deterministic or stochastic is detected by whether it commutes with copying.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- What's a Markov category -->
    <h3>What's a Markov category</h3>
    <p>A <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_category">🅦 Markov category</a> is a category where morphisms are stochastic functions (Markov kernels) and you can copy and discard data. The paradigmatic example is <strong>FinStoch</strong>: objects are finite sets, morphisms are <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_matrix">🅦 stochastic matrices</a>.</p>
    <p>In Python: a stochastic function takes an input and returns a probability distribution over outputs. A distribution is a dict mapping outcomes to probabilities.</p>

    <Repl client:load initialCode={`# A Markov kernel: input -> distribution over outputs
# This is a morphism in FinStoch.

def fair_coin(x):
    """Ignore input, return heads/tails 50/50"""
    return {"heads": 0.5, "tails": 0.5}

def biased_die(x):
    """Ignore input, return 1-6 with bias toward 6"""
    return {1: 0.1, 2: 0.1, 3: 0.1, 4: 0.1, 5: 0.1, 6: 0.5}

def deterministic_double(x):
    """Deterministic: always returns exactly 2x"""
    return {x * 2: 1.0}

print("fair_coin:", fair_coin(None))
print("biased_die:", biased_die(None))
print("double(3):", deterministic_double(3))
print()
print("All three are morphisms in FinStoch.")
print("The first two are stochastic. The third is deterministic.")
`} />

    <!-- Copy and determinism -->
    <h3>Copy detects determinism</h3>
    <p>Every object in a Markov category has a <strong>copy</strong> morphism: ν(x) = (x, x). Fritz's key insight: a morphism f is <strong>deterministic</strong> if and only if it commutes with copy. "Apply then copy" equals "copy then apply to both copies."</p>
    <p>Stochastic functions fail this test. If you flip a coin and then copy the result, you get (heads, heads) or (tails, tails). If you copy first and then flip each independently, you can get (heads, tails). Different distributions — the function is stochastic.</p>

