    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>All examples use finite dicts as distributions over small sets. Fritz's paper works over arbitrary measurable spaces, Borel categories, and continuous distributions. The copy-naturality test is exact for the finite case. The informativeness preorder example is a simplified illustration — the full definition involves almost-sure factorization, not pointwise equality. Every example is <strong class="text-green-400">Simplified</strong> unless marked otherwise.</p>

